# Test Desiderata

Optimize the value of your tests by choosing how to balance various valuable properties. Tests should maximize value while making intentional trade-offs between competing properties.

Reference: [Test Desiderata](https://testdesiderata.com/)

## Core Properties

### 1. Isolated
**Tests should return the same results regardless of the order in which they are run.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
const setup = () => {
  reset(); // Clear all state before each test
  registerTestInfrastructure();
  
  return {
    useCase: new MyUseCase(),
    fakeRepository: inject(tokenFakeMyRepository),
  };
};

it('should create user', async () => {
  const { useCase, fakeRepository } = setup();
  // Each test gets fresh dependencies
});
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
// Shared state between tests
let sharedRepository: FakeRepository;

beforeAll(() => {
  sharedRepository = new FakeRepository(); // Reused across tests
});

it('test 1', async () => {
  await sharedRepository.save(user); // Affects next test
});

it('test 2', async () => {
  const users = await sharedRepository.findAll(); // Depends on test 1
});
```

### 2. Composable
**Test different dimensions of variability separately and combine the results.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
// Test each dimension independently
describe('user validation', () => {
  it('should validate email format', () => {
    const user = UserMother.basic().withEmail('invalid').build();
    expect(() => validateUser(user)).toThrow();
  });
  
  it('should validate age range', () => {
    const user = UserMother.basic().withAge(-1).build();
    expect(() => validateUser(user)).toThrow();
  });
});

// Combine when testing integration
describe('user creation', () => {
  it('should create valid user', () => {
    const user = UserMother.basic()
      .withEmail('valid@email.com')
      .withAge(25)
      .build();
    expect(() => createUser(user)).not.toThrow();
  });
});
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
// Testing multiple dimensions at once
it('should validate user completely', () => {
  // Tests email, age, name, etc. all together
  // If it fails, which validation failed?
});
```

### 3. Deterministic
**If nothing changes, the test result shouldn't change.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
it('should format date consistently', () => {
  const date = new Date('2025-01-20T10:00:00Z'); // Fixed date
  const formatted = formatDate(date);
  expect(formatted).toBe('2025-01-20');
});

it('should generate ID deterministically', () => {
  const generator = new TestIDGenerator('fixed-seed');
  expect(generator.next()).toBe('test-id-1');
});
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
it('should create timestamp', () => {
  const timestamp = Date.now(); // Non-deterministic
  expect(timestamp).toBeGreaterThan(0); // Will vary on each run
});

it('should generate random ID', () => {
  const id = Math.random().toString(); // Non-deterministic
  expect(id).toBeTruthy();
});
```

### 4. Fast
**Tests should run quickly.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
// Use in-memory fakes
const setup = () => {
  reset();
  registerTestInfrastructure(); // Registers fast fakes
  
  return {
    useCase: new MyUseCase(),
    fakeClockify: inject(tokenFakeClockifyService), // In-memory
  };
};

it('should fetch projects quickly', async () => {
  const { useCase, fakeClockify } = setup();
  fakeClockify.projects.set('id', ProjectMother.basic().build());
  
  const result = await useCase.getProject({ id: 'id' }); // Instant
  expect(result).toBeDefined();
});
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
// Using real external services
it('should fetch from real Clockify API', async () => {
  const api = new ClockifyAPI(process.env.API_KEY);
  const result = await api.getProjects(); // Slow network call
});

// Unnecessary delays
it('should wait', async () => {
  await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 5000));
});
```

### 5. Writable
**Tests should be cheap to write relative to the cost of the code being tested.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
// Use Mothers for quick test data creation
it('should create allocation', async () => {
  const { useCase } = setup();
  
  const args = UploadUserAllocationArgsMother.basic().build();
  
  await useCase.execute(args);
  // Test written in 3 lines
});

// Reusable setup function
const setup = () => {
  reset();
  registerTestInfrastructure();
  return { useCase: new MyUseCase() };
};
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
// Manually constructing complex objects every time
it('should create allocation', async () => {
  const user = {
    id: 'user-1',
    email: 'test@example.com',
    name: 'Test User',
    clockifyId: 'clockify-1',
    slackId: 'slack-1',
    role: 'developer',
    status: 'active',
    createdAt: new Date(),
    updatedAt: new Date(),
    // ... 20 more fields
  };
  
  const project = {
    // ... another 15 fields
  };
  
  // Lots of boilerplate for each test
});
```

### 6. Readable
**Tests should be comprehensible for the reader, invoking the motivation for writing this particular test.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
describe('SendAllocationFormsUseCase', () => {
  describe('when user has active assignments', () => {
    it('should send allocation form to user', async () => {
      const { useCase, fakeSlack } = setup();
      
      // Arrange: User with active assignment
      const user = UserMother.basic().build();
      const assignment = AssignmentMother.active()
        .withUser(user)
        .build();
      
      // Act: Send forms
      await useCase.execute();
      
      // Assert: Slack message sent
      expect(fakeSlack.sentMessages).toHaveLength(1);
      expect(fakeSlack.sentMessages[0].userId).toBe(user.slackId);
    });
  });
  
  describe('when user has no assignments', () => {
    it('should not send any forms', async () => {
      const { useCase, fakeSlack } = setup();
      // Clear motivation: testing empty state
      
      await useCase.execute();
      
      expect(fakeSlack.sentMessages).toHaveLength(0);
    });
  });
});
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
it('test1', async () => {
  const x = setup();
  const y = { a: 1, b: 2, c: 3 };
  await x.do(y);
  expect(x.z).toBe(4);
  // What is this testing? Why?
});
```

### 7. Behavioral
**Tests should be sensitive to changes in the behavior of the code under test.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
it('should send form to users with allocations below threshold', async () => {
  const { useCase, fakeSlack } = setup();
  
  const userLowAllocation = UserMother.basic()
    .withId('low')
    .build();
  const userHighAllocation = UserMother.basic()
    .withId('high')
    .build();
  
  fakeClockify.setAllocation(userLowAllocation.id, 50); // Below 80%
  fakeClockify.setAllocation(userHighAllocation.id, 100); // Above 80%
  
  await useCase.execute();
  
  // Tests the business behavior: who gets the form
  expect(fakeSlack.sentMessages).toContainEqual(
    expect.objectContaining({ userId: userLowAllocation.slackId })
  );
  expect(fakeSlack.sentMessages).not.toContainEqual(
    expect.objectContaining({ userId: userHighAllocation.slackId })
  );
});
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
it('should call calculateAllocation', async () => {
  const spy = vitest.spyOn(service, 'calculateAllocation');
  await useCase.execute();
  expect(spy).toHaveBeenCalled(); // Tests implementation, not behavior
});
```

### 8. Structure-Insensitive
**Tests should not change their result if the structure of the code changes.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
// Test the public interface
it('should get projects grouped by client', async () => {
  const { useCase } = setup();
  
  const result = await useCase.execute({ workspaceId: 'ws-1' });
  
  // Assert on the output, not how it's computed
  expect(result).toEqual({
    'Client A': [project1, project2],
    'Client B': [project3],
  });
});
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
// Test internal structure
it('should call private method in correct order', async () => {
  const { useCase } = setup();
  const spy1 = vitest.spyOn(useCase as any, '_fetchProjects');
  const spy2 = vitest.spyOn(useCase as any, '_groupByClient');
  
  await useCase.execute({ workspaceId: 'ws-1' });
  
  // If we refactor and merge methods, test breaks
  expect(spy1).toHaveBeenCalledBefore(spy2);
});
```

### 9. Automated
**Tests should run without human intervention.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
// Tests run automatically in CI/CD
// See: .github/workflows/run-tests.yml

// Use assertions, not console.log
it('should validate input', () => {
  const result = validate(input);
  expect(result.isValid).toBe(true);
});
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
it('should show result', () => {
  const result = calculate(5, 10);
  console.log('Check if result is 15:', result);
  // Requires human to check console
});

it('manual test', () => {
  // TODO: manually verify in browser
  expect(true).toBe(true);
});
```

### 10. Specific
**If a test fails, the cause of the failure should be obvious.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
describe('user email validation', () => {
  it('should reject email without @', () => {
    const user = UserMother.basic()
      .withEmail('invalidemail.com')
      .build();
    
    expect(() => validateUser(user))
      .toThrow('Email must contain @');
  });
  
  it('should reject email without domain', () => {
    const user = UserMother.basic()
      .withEmail('user@')
      .build();
    
    expect(() => validateUser(user))
      .toThrow('Email must have domain');
  });
});
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
it('should validate user', () => {
  // Tests many things at once
  const user = UserMother.basic()
    .withEmail('invalid')
    .withAge(-1)
    .withName('')
    .build();
  
  expect(() => validateUser(user)).toThrow();
  // Which validation failed?
});
```

### 11. Predictive
**If the tests all pass, then the code under test should be suitable for production.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
// Test real-world scenarios
describe('allocation form workflow', () => {
  it('should handle complete user journey', async () => {
    const { useCase, fakeClockify, fakeSlack } = setup();
    
    // Setup production-like data
    const users = [
      UserMother.active().withAllocation(50).build(),
      UserMother.active().withAllocation(90).build(),
    ];
    
    await useCase.sendForms();
    await useCase.processResponses();
    await useCase.syncToClockify();
    
    // Verify end-to-end behavior
    expect(fakeClockify.allocations).toHaveLength(2);
  });
  
  it('should handle API failures gracefully', async () => {
    const { useCase, fakeSlack } = setup();
    fakeSlack.simulateError(new Error('Network timeout'));
    
    await expect(useCase.execute()).rejects.toThrow('Network timeout');
  });
});
```

❌ **Don't:**
```typescript
// Only test happy path
it('should work', async () => {
  const result = await useCase.execute();
  expect(result).toBeDefined();
  // What about errors? Edge cases? Real scenarios?
});
```

### 12. Inspiring
**Passing the tests should inspire confidence.**

✅ **Do:**
```typescript
// Comprehensive test coverage
describe('SendAllocationFormsUseCase', () => {
  describe('happy path', () => {
    it('should send forms to eligible users', async () => { /* ... */ });
  });
  
  describe('error handling', () => {
    it('should retry on temporary failure', async () => { /* ... */ });
    it('should log permanent failures', async () => { /* ... */ });
  });
  
  describe('edge cases', () => {
    it('should handle users with no Slack ID', async () => { /* ... */ });
    it('should handle empty workspace', async () => { /* ... */ });
  });
  
  describe('validation', () => {
    it('should reject invalid workspace ID', async () => { /* ... */ });
  });
});

// When all pass, you can deploy with confidence
```

## Balancing Trade-offs

### Fast vs. Predictive

**Trade-off:** More realistic tests (predictive) often run slower.

**Solution:** Use test pyramids. Fast unit tests with fakes for most cases, slower integration tests for critical paths.

```typescript
// Fast: Unit test with fakes (most tests)
it('should process allocation', async () => {
  const { useCase, fakeClockify } = setup();
  // Runs in milliseconds
});

// Predictive: Integration test (fewer tests)
it('should integrate with real Clockify SDK', async () => {
  // Uses real SDK in test mode
  // Runs in seconds, but more realistic
});
```

### Readable vs. Writable

**Trade-off:** Very readable tests can be verbose to write.

**Solution:** Use Mothers and setup functions to make tests both readable and writable.

```typescript
// Readable AND writable
it('should send form to user with low allocation', async () => {
  const { useCase } = setup(); // Easy to write
  
  const user = UserMother.active() // Easy to write
    .withLowAllocation() // Readable intent
    .build();
  
  await useCase.execute();
  
  expect(/* ... */); // Clear assertion
});
```

### Isolated vs. Fast

**Trade-off:** Resetting state for isolation can slow tests.

**Solution:** Use lightweight in-memory fakes that reset quickly.

```typescript
const setup = () => {
  reset(); // Fast - just clears Map/Set in memory
  registerTestInfrastructure(); // Registers lightweight fakes
  
  return {
    useCase: new MyUseCase(),
    fakes: {
      clockify: inject(tokenFakeClockifyService),
      slack: inject(tokenFakeSlackService),
    },
  };
};
```

## Checklist for High-Value Tests

When writing tests, aim to maximize:

- [ ] **Isolated** - Each test resets state with `reset()`
- [ ] **Composable** - Test one dimension at a time
- [ ] **Deterministic** - Use fixed dates, IDs, seeds
- [ ] **Fast** - Use in-memory fakes, no real I/O
- [ ] **Writable** - Use Mothers, reusable setup
- [ ] **Readable** - Clear describe/it structure, meaningful names
- [ ] **Behavioral** - Test outputs/side-effects, not implementation
- [ ] **Structure-Insensitive** - Test public interface only
- [ ] **Automated** - No manual steps, runs in CI
- [ ] **Specific** - One assertion dimension per test
- [ ] **Predictive** - Cover happy path, errors, edge cases
- [ ] **Inspiring** - Comprehensive coverage of critical paths

